{
  "verdict": "correct",
  "notes": "The argument is valid: in any lattice (hence in any Boolean algebra), $a\\wedge b\\le a$ because $a\\wedge b$ is a greatest lower bound of $\\{a,b\\}$, so it is in particular a lower bound of $a$. Also, if $x\\le y$ then $y\\vee x=y$ since $y$ is an upper bound of $\\{x,y\\}$ and $y\\vee x$ is the least such upper bound. Applying this with $x=a\\wedge b$ and $y=a$ yields $a\\vee(a\\wedge b)=a$ (absorption)."
}

